           <h1 id="semname" style="margin-bottom: 2px;"><span itemprop="name">Effectively Using Java Packages And Features Training Seminar</span></h1> 
           <span class="smalltype" id="semattendee"><i>presented by <a class="smalltype" href="/Seminar-Providers/Hands-On-Technology-Transfer-Inc/2179/index.aspx"><span itemprop="attendee">Hands-On Technology Transfer, Inc</span></a></i><br> 
            <div id="semimage">
             <img src="/img/vn/hott1.gif" alt="View the Hands-On Technology Transfer, Inc" itemprop="image" style="margin-top:16px;">
            </div> </span> 
           <div class="orange_outlinebox">
            <p class="smalltype" style="margin-top: 8px;"><a class="lnkOrange" href="/onsite_request.aspx?id=8631">Bring a trainer to your location</a> to deliver this class for groups of 10 or more.</p>
           </div> 
           <h2 style="margin-top: 15px;">Summary</h2> 
           <h3 id="semdesc" class="logo_blue_summ"><span itemprop="description">This intermediate level course is intended for programmers who already have a fundamental understanding of Java programming and some experience writing code. </span></h3> 
           <h3 style="margin-top: 15px;"><b>Course Topics:</b> <a class="smalltype" href="/Training-Categories/Computers---IT/111/index.aspx">Computers / IT Training</a> &gt; <a class="smalltype" href="/Training-Topics/Software-Development/18/index.aspx">Software Development</a>&nbsp; <a class="smalltype" href="/feeds/subcategoryfeed.aspx?id=18&amp;rID=86"><img src="/img/smrssfeed.png" alt="View/subscribe to this subcategory's RSS Feed"></a></h3> 
           <h2 style="margin-top: 15px;"><b>Workshop Description/Agenda</b></h2> 
           <div id="ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_formview1_Panel5" style="margin-bottom: 20px;"> 
            <div id="learnbox"> 
             <div id="learnbg"> 
              <strong>Students Will Learn:</strong>
             </div> 
             <div id="leftul"> 
              <ul> 
               <li>Using Reflection and Introspection with Java Classes <span class="courier">(java.lang.reflect package)</span></li> 
               <li>Writing Type Safe and Reliable Code with the Enhanced Capabilities of Java 5</li> 
               <li>Using the Java Collections Framework <span class="courier"> (java.util package)</span></li> 
               <li>Processing Databases Using JDBC <span class="courier">(java.sql package)</span></li> 
              </ul> 
             </div> 
             <div id="rightul"> 
              <ul> 
               <li>Creating, Controlling, and Synchronizing Threads</li> 
               <li>Creating and Using Inner and Nested Classes</li> 
               <li>Using Networking Related Classes <span class="courier">(java.net package)</span></li> 
               <li>Creating Client/Server Programs</li> 
              </ul> 
             </div> 
            </div> 
            <p><strong>Course Description</strong>: This intermediate level course is intended for programmers who already have a fundamental understanding of Java programming and some experience writing code. It provides additional insights and details regarding some of the more advanced and useful capabilities contained in the Java programming language and its associated packages. Topics include reflection and JavaBeans, Java 5 type safety enhancements, the Java Collections Framework, Java Database Connectivity (JDBC), multithreading, inner classes, and networking.</p> 
            <p><strong>Course Prerequisites</strong>: Familiarity with and experience using Java. Completion of either the "Learning to Program with Java", "Java for COBOL Programmers", or "Java Programming" course, or equivalent Java programming experience.</p> 
            <div id="coursebg">
              Effectively Using Java Packages And Features Course Overview:
            </div> 
            <br> 
            <table class="coursetable"> 
             <tbody>
              <tr> 
               <td><strong>JavaBeans, Reflection, and Introspection</strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>JavaBean Requirements </li> 
                 <li>Determining Type of an Object </li> 
                 <li>Reflection Overview and Uses </li> 
                 <li>Reflection Issues </li> 
                 <li>Reflection Using Class Object </li> 
                 <li>Invoking Methods Using Reflection </li> 
                 <li>Methods Available on the Class Object </li> 
                 <li>Creating A New Instance </li> 
                 <li>Introspection </li> 
                 <li>Customizing BeanInfo </li> 
                 <li>Invoking Methods Using Introspection </li> 
                 <li>Using Reflection to Access Properties </li> 
                 <li>Review of Equals Method</li> 
                </ul> </td> 
               <td><strong>Type Safety and Java 5 Enhancements</strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>Annotations 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Standard Annotations </li> 
                   <li>User Defined Annotations </li> 
                   <li>Reflection Annotation Information </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Enum Data Type </li> 
                 <li>Generics </li> 
                 <li>Autoboxing </li> 
                 <li>Methods Having Variable Parameters </li> 
                 <li>Assertions </li> 
                </ul> </td> 
              </tr> 
              <tr> 
               <td><strong>Collections Framework</strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>What is the Collections Framework </li> 
                 <li>Simple Arrays and Arrays of Objects</li> 
                 <li>Legacy Container Classes </li> 
                 <li>Collections Framework Overview </li> 
                 <li>Collections Interfaces 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Lists </li> 
                   <li>Sets </li> 
                   <li>Queues </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Map Interfaces </li> 
                 <li>Interface Implementations 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Lists </li> 
                   <li>Sets </li> 
                   <li>Queues</li> 
                   <li>Maps </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Iterators</li> 
                </ul> </td> 
               <td><strong>JDBC </strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>What is JDBC </li> 
                 <li>JDBC Drivers </li> 
                 <li>Accessing the Database 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Loading Driver </li> 
                   <li>Connecting to Data Source </li> 
                   <li>Creating Statements </li> 
                   <li>Executing Statements </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Processing Result Sets 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Cursor Positioning </li> 
                   <li>Column Retrieval </li> 
                   <li>Updating Result Sets </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Connection Pooling </li> 
                 <li>Processing Errors and Warnings</li> 
                 <li>Using Prepared Statements </li> 
                 <li>Using Stored Procedures </li> 
                 <li>Metadata 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Result Set Metadata</li> 
                   <li>Database Metadata </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Transaction Processing </li> 
                 <li>Isolation Levels </li> 
                 <li>SQL Batches</li> 
                </ul> </td> 
              </tr> 
              <tr> 
               <td><strong>Threads</strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>Definition of Thread </li> 
                 <li>Creating Threads </li> 
                 <li>Naming Threads </li> 
                 <li>Data Sharing Among Threads 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Local Data </li> 
                   <li>Instance Data </li> 
                   <li>Class Data </li> 
                   <li>Volatile Keyword </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Thread States </li> 
                 <li>Thread Priority 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Minimum. Maximum, Normal Priorities </li> 
                   <li>Preemptive Thread Priority </li> 
                   <li><span class="courier">setPriority</span> Method </li> 
                   <li><span class="courier">getPriority</span> Method </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Piping Data Between Threads </li> 
                 <li>Coordination and Controlling Threads </li> 
                 <li>Synchronizing Threads 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Why Synchronization is Needed </li> 
                   <li>Producer/Consumer Example </li> 
                   <li>Synchronized Keyword </li> 
                   <li>Thread Synchronization Methods</li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                </ul> </td> 
               <td><strong>Networking</strong> 
                <ul> 
                 <li>Overview of <span class="courier">java.net</span> Package </li> 
                 <li>Format of URL </li> 
                 <li>URL Class </li> 
                 <li>URLConnection Class</li> 
                 <li>InetAddress Class </li> 
                 <li>Definitions 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Client </li> 
                   <li>Server </li> 
                   <li>Port </li> 
                   <li>Socket </li> 
                  </ul> </li> 
                 <li>Socket Class 
                  <ul> 
                   <li>Writing Client Side Applications </li>
